oincidence event category we focus on the CC channel with the ground state ${ }^{13} \\mathrm{~N}$ and consider the channel with the excited ${ }^{13} \\mathrm{~N}\\left(3 / 2^{-} ; 3.502 \\mathrm{MeV}\\right)$ as a component of the total singles spectrum as illustrated in Fig. 2.\n\nAmong the five listed NC channels, the only one with a coincidence signature is the interaction of $\\nu_{x}+{ }^{13} \\mathrm{C} \\rightarrow$ $\\nu_{x}+n+{ }^{12} \\mathrm{C}$, with a prompt $\\gamma$ energy of 4.44 MeV from ${ }^{12} \\mathrm{C}$ de-excitation and the delayed neutron capture. However, given that the background from the inverse beta decay interactions of reactor antineutrinos are overwhelming, where the signal to background ratio is at the level of $10^{-4}$, and thus the event rate of this channel is unobservable. In this work we focus on the NC channels with the signature of single $\\gamma$ deexcitation, among which the NC interaction with the ${ }^{13} \\mathrm{C}$ de-excited energy of 3.685 MeV :\n\n$$\n\\nu_{x}+{ }^{13} \\mathrm{C} \\rightarrow \\nu_{x}+{ }^{13} \\mathrm{C}\\left(\\frac{3}{2}^{-} ; 3.685 \\mathrm{MeV}\\right)\n$$\n\nis the dominant interaction channel and will be used to determine the ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ solar neutrino flux via the NC interaction.\nFinally, we also consider the ES interaction channel on the electron,\n\n$$\n\\nu_{x}+e \\rightarrow \\nu_{x}+e\n$$\n\nwhere the signature is a single recoiled electron (Abusleme et al. 2021a). Using all the three channels of CC, NC, ES interactions, we are able to make a model independent measurement of the ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ solar neutrino flux, $\\sin ^{2} \\theta_{12}$ and $\\Delta m_{21}^{2}$"
