-night asymmetry of the solar neutrino observation, in which the signal rate in the night is higher than that in the day due to $\\nu_{x}$ regeneration inside the Earth.\nIn this work, in addition to the visible energy spectra of the CC, NC and ES channels, we also consider the day-night asymmetry to constrain the neutrino oscillation parameters. The location of JUNO (i.e., $112^{\\circ} 31^{\\prime} 05^{\\prime \\prime} \\mathrm{E}$ and $22^{\\circ} 07^{\\prime} 05^{\\prime \\prime}$ N (Abusleme et al. 2022a)) is used in the day-night asymmetry calculations, and the two dimensional visible energy and zenith angle spectra are employed. For illustration, we show in Fig. 3 the ratios of solar neutrino signal event rates with and without considering the terrestrial matter effects as the function of the zenith angle $\\theta_{z}$. The red and blue solid lines are for the ES and CC channels, respectively. In comparison, the dashed lines are shown for the respective averages over the whole zenith angle range. The ratios of the day-night average $\\left(R_{\\mathrm{A}}\\right)$, the daytime $\\left(R_{\\mathrm{D}}\\right)$, and the nighttime $\\left(R_{\\mathrm{N}}\\right)$ are also illustrated with the first three bins. The error bars are quoted as the statistical uncertainties of the signal and backgrounds. The blue shaded regions with different colors from the left to right are used to denote the zenith angle ranges passing through the crust, mantle and core of the Earth respectively. The day-night asymmetry, defined as $\\left(R_{\\mathrm{D}}-R_{\\mathrm{N}}\\right) / R_{\\mathrm{A}}$, is predicted to be $-3.1 \\%$ and $-1.6 \\%$ for the CC and ES channels respectively. The energy ranges of the CC and ES channels are $[5,14] \\mathrm{MeV}$ and $[2,16] \\mathrm{MeV}$ respectively. Given that all the neutrino flavors can be detected through the NC channel, no day-night asymmetry exists in the NC detection. Note that the magnitude of the day-night asymmetry strongly depends on the value of $\\Delta m_{21}^{2}$. If $\\Delta m_{21}^{2}$ is decreased from the KamLAND measurement $7.5 \\times 10^{-5} \\mathrm{eV}^{2}$ (Gando et al. 2013) to $6.1 \\times 10^{-5} \\mathrm{eV}^{2}$ of the global solar neutrino data (Esteban et al. 2020), the absolute values of the day-night asymmetry are also increased to $-4.2 \\%$ and $-2.2 \\%$ for the CC and ES channels, respectively.\n\n## 3. SENSITIVITY STUDY\n\nIn this section, we study the physical potential for the model independent measurement of ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ solar neutrinos using CC, NC, and ES channels. Based on the typical event signatures, the full solar neutrino data can be separated into the correlated and single event data sets. As discussed in the previous section, all the three interaction channels from"
