      "markdown": "Table 3. Description the nuisance parameters and the associated uncertainties in the $\\chi^{2}$ function.\n\n| Sys. | Description for the pull term | Uncertainty |\n| :--: | :--: | :--: |\n| $\\varepsilon_{X}^{\\mathrm{ES}}, \\varepsilon_{X}^{\\mathrm{NC}}, \\varepsilon_{X}^{\\mathrm{CC}}$ | Cross section for the CC, NC, ES channels | $1 \\%, 1 \\%, 0.5 \\%$ |\n| $\\varepsilon_{\\text {eff }}^{\\mathrm{C}}, \\varepsilon_{\\text {eff }}^{\\mathrm{S}}$ | Detector efficiency | $2 \\%$ (Abusleme et al. 2021a) |\n| $\\varepsilon_{\\mathrm{B}}^{\\mathrm{CC}}, \\varepsilon_{\\mathrm{B}}^{\\mathrm{ES}}$ | Rate for the $k_{\\mathrm{C}}$-th or $k_{0}$-th background component | $1 \\%-10 \\%$, same as Abusleme et al. (2021a) |\n| $\\varepsilon_{\\mathrm{s}}$ | ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ neutrino energy spectrum | Bahcall et al. (1996); Bahcall (1997) |\n\nwhere $S_{\\text {pre }}^{\\mathrm{CC}}, S_{\\text {pre }}^{\\mathrm{NC}}$, and $S_{\\text {pre }}^{\\mathrm{ES}}$ represent the two-dimensional spectra of the ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ neutrino signals in the CC, NC, and ES channels, respectively, incorporating the fiducial volume and signal efficiencies. The projections of these spectra onto the visible energy axis are depicted in Fig. 1 for the CC channel and Fig. 2 for the NC and ES channels. Meanwhile, $B_{\\text {pre }}^{k_{\\mathrm{C}}}$ and $B_{\\text {pre }}^{k_{\\mathrm{S}}}$ correspond to the background components in the correlated and single event samples, respectively, with their visible energy spectra illustrated in the same figures. The calculations of the ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ neutrino signal spectra in the $\\mathrm{CC}, \\mathrm{NC}$, and ES channels are as follows:\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\nS_{\\mathrm{pre}}^{\\mathrm{CC}}\\left(\\theta_{z}^{i}, E_{\\mathrm{vis}}^{j_{\\mathrm{C}}}\\right)= & \\Phi_{\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{B}}} \\times\\left[\\left(1+\\varepsilon_{\\mathrm{s}} \\delta_{E_{\\nu}}^{\\mathrm{S}}\\right) S_{\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{B}}}\\left(E_{\\nu}\\right) \\times P_{\\mathrm{e} e}\\left(\\theta_{12}, \\Delta m_{21}^{2}, E_{\\nu}, \\theta_{z}^{i}\\right)\\right. \\\\\n& \\left.\\times\\left(1+\\varepsilon_{X}^{\\mathrm{CC}}\\right) \\otimes \\sigma_{\\mathrm{CC}}\\left(E_{\\nu}, E_{e}\\right) \\otimes M\\left(E_{e}, E_{\\mathrm{vis}}^{j_{\\mathrm{C}}}\\right)\\right] \\\\\nS_{\\mathrm{pre}}^{\\mathrm{NC}}\\left(\\theta_{z}^{i}, E_{\\mathrm{vis}}^{j_{\\mathrm{C}}}\\right)= & \\Phi_{\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{B}}} \\times\\left[\\left(1+\\varepsilon_{\\mathrm{s}} \\delta_{E_{\\nu}}^{\\mathrm{S}}\\right) S_{\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{B}}}\\left(E_{\\nu}\\right)\\right. \\\\\n& \\left.\\times\\left(1+\\varepsilon_{X}^{\\mathrm{NC}}\\right) \\otimes \\sigma_{\\mathrm{NC}}\\left(E_{\\nu}, E_{\\gamma}\\right) \\otimes M\\left(E_{\\gamma}, E_{\\mathrm{vis}}^{j_{\\mathrm{C}}}\\right)\\right] \\\\\nS_{\\mathrm{pre}}^{\\mathrm{ES}}\\left(\\theta_{z}^{i}, E_{\\mathrm{vis}}^{j_{\\mathrm{C}}}\\right)= & \\Phi_{\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{B}}} \\times\\left\\{\\left(1+\\varepsilon_{\\mathrm{s}} \\delta_{E_{\\nu}}^{\\mathrm{S}}\\right) S_{\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{B}}}\\left(E_{\\nu}\\right) \\times \\Sigma_{\\alpha}\\left[P_{\\mathrm{e} \\alpha}\\left(\\theta_{12}, \\Delta m_{21}^{2}, E_{\\nu}, \\theta_{z}^{i}\\right)\\right.\\right. \\\\\n& \\left.\\left.\\times\\left(1+\\varepsilon_{X}^{\\mathrm{ES}}\\right) \\otimes \\sigma_{\\mathrm{ES}}^{\\nu_{\\alpha}}\\left(E_{\\nu}, E_{e}\\right)\\right] \\otimes M\\left(E_{e}, E_{\\mathrm{vis}}^{j_{\\mathrm{C}}}\\right)\\right\\}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nThe ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ neutrino signal spectra for the $\\mathrm{CC}, \\mathrm{NC}$, and ES channels are calculated by multiplying the ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ neutrino spectrum $S_{\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{B}}}$ with the neutrino oscillation probability $P_{\\mathrm{e} \\alpha}$ (where $\\alpha$ equals $e$ or $\\mu+\\tau$ ), and then convolving the resulting product with the differential interaction cross sections (namely, $\\sigma_{\\mathrm{CC}}, \\sigma_{\\mathrm{NC}}$, and $\\sigma_{\\mathrm{ES}}^{\\nu_{\\alpha}}$ ) as well as with the detector response matrix $M$. The neutrino oscillation probability $P_{\\mathrm{e} \\alpha}$ includes both the standard MSW flavor conversion and terrestrial matter effects, and is a function of the neutrino energy $E_{\\nu}$ and the zenith angle $\\theta_{z}$, calculated within the three-neutrino oscillation framework. The detector response matrix $M$ accounts for the effects of energy resolution and energy non-linearity, as described in Abusleme et al. (2021a). The observed spectra $N_{\\text {obs }}^{\\mathrm{C}}\\left(\\theta_{z}^{i}, E_{\\text {vis }}^{j_{\\mathrm{C}}}\\right)$ and $N_{\\text {obs }}^{\\mathrm{S}}\\left(\\theta_{z}^{i}, E_{\\text {vis }}^{j_{\\mathrm{S}}}\\right)$ are obtained from the corresponding predicted spectra by applying the true values of the ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ neutrino flux $\\Phi_{\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{B}}}$, oscillation parameters $\\sin ^{2} \\theta_{12}$, and $\\Delta m_{21}^{2}$, and assuming negligible contributions from nuisance parameters. Note that, as discussed in Sec. 2, the ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ solar neutrino interactions may also contribute to the background components $B_{\\text {pre }}^{k_{\\mathrm{C}}}$ (e.g., the green line in Fig. 1, the purple line in Fig. 2), In such instances, all correlations between the signal and background components are accounted for in the $\\chi^{2}$ function.\n\nThe nuisance parameters $\\varepsilon_{X}^{m}(m=\\mathrm{CC}, \\mathrm{NC}, \\mathrm{ES}), \\varepsilon_{\\mathrm{B}}^{k}, \\varepsilon_{\\text {eff }}^{n}(n=\\mathrm{C}, \\mathrm{S})$ account for systematic uncertainties associated with the cross section, the backgrounds, and the detection efficiency, respectively, as discussed in the manuscript. The parameter $\\delta_{E_{\\nu}}^{\\mathrm{S}}$ represents the $1 \\sigma$ fractional variation of the ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ neutrino energy spectrum, as detailed in Bahcall et al. (1996); Bahcall (1997), while $\\varepsilon_{\\mathrm{s}}$ denotes the magnitude of the ${ }^{8} \\mathrm{~B}$ neutrino spectral uncertainty. A summary of the nuisance parameters and their corresponding uncertainties within the $\\chi^{2}$ function is summarized in Table 3."
